{
  "action_id": "851",
  "action_title": "Use shelterwood harvesting instead of clearcutting",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nThree studies (including two randomized, replicated, controlled, before-and-after studies) in the USA found that compared to clearcutting, shelterwood harvesting resulted in higher, similar or initially higher and then similar salamander abundance. A meta-analysis of 24 studies in North  America\u00a0found that partial harvest, which included shelterwood harvesting with three other types, resulted in smaller reductions in salamander populations than clearcutting\nTwo of three studies (including two randomized, replicated, controlled, before-and-after studies) in the USA found that compared to no harvesting, shelterwood harvesting decreased salamander abundance and changed species composition. One found that shelterwood harvesting did not affect salamander abundance.\nOne randomized, replicated, controlled, before-and-after study in the USA found that compared to unharvested plots, the proportion of female salamanders carrying eggs, eggs per female or proportion of juveniles were similar or lower in harvested plots that included shelterwood harvested plots, depending on species and time since harvest."
}

{
  "action_id": "844",
  "action_title": "Harvest groups of trees instead of clearcutting",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nThree studies (including two randomized, replicated, controlled, before-and-after studies) in the USA found that compared to clearcutting, harvesting trees in small groups did not result in higher amphibian or salamander abundance. A meta-analysis of 24 studies in North America\u00a0found that partial harvest, which included harvesting groups or individual trees, thinning and shelterwood harvesting, resulted in smaller reductions in salamander populations than clearcutting\nTwo studies (including one randomized, replicated, controlled, before-and-after study) in the USA found that compared to no harvesting, harvesting trees in small groups significantly decreased salamander abundance and changed species composition.\nOne randomized, replicated, controlled, before-and-after study in the USA found that compared to unharvested plots, the proportion of female salamanders carrying eggs were similar and proportion of eggs per female and juveniles similar or lower in harvested plots that included harvest of groups of trees."
}

{
  "query": "How do different partial harvesting methods in USA forests compare to clearcutting in their impact on salamander populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across USA forests, shelterwood harvesting compared to clearcutting resulted in salamander abundance that was higher, similar, or initially higher then similar, and a meta-analysis reported that partial harvests including shelterwood caused smaller reductions in salamander populations than clearcutting [851]. Harvesting groups of trees did not yield higher amphibian or salamander abundance than clearcutting in three USA studies, though a meta-analysis found that partial harvests including group selection produced smaller reductions in salamander populations than clearcutting [844]. Thinning showed higher abundance or a less negative overall response than clearcuts in some studies, with other studies showing mixed effects by species and time since harvest; emigrating salamanders used thinned stands significantly more than clearcuts; and a meta-analysis found that partial harvests including thinning produced smaller reductions in salamander populations than clearcutting [852].",
  "action_ids": [
    "851",
    "844",
    "852"
  ]
}

