{
  "query": "What design and placement factors are associated with the successful use of road tunnels by migrating amphibians?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Tunnel dimensions and geometry: Wider-diameter culverts/tunnels were used more in three of six studies, and longer tunnels were avoided in one of two studies [884].\n- Lighting: Tunnel lighting affected use in all three studies that tested it, with mixed effects reported [884].\n- Substrate: Natural substrates inside tunnels were used more in three of six studies [884].\n- Water presence: The presence of water had mixed effects in two of three studies; culverts with flowing water were used by amphibians in multiple studies and were used more or the same amount as dry culverts in some cases [884].\n- Entrance location and tunnel climate: Entrance location affected use in one study, and tunnel climate affected use in one study [884].\n- Guidance and fencing: The majority of tunnels studied had barrier fencing to guide amphibians to entrances [884]; installing culverts/tunnels decreased amphibian road deaths in most studies, including cases where reductions occurred only when barrier fencing was also installed [884]. Barrier fencing with culverts decreased road deaths when fence length and material were effective [756]. Barriers at least 0.6 m high were required to prevent green frogs and leopard frogs from climbing over, though treefrogs and around 10% of common toads were recorded climbing over barriers during breeding migrations [756].\n- Design cautions: One-way tunnels with vertical entry chutes led to high mortality of common toads, and condensation deposits from steel culverts had very high metal concentrations [884].",
