{
  "query": "For road mitigation projects, what design factors are associated with the success or failure of tunnels and culverts for amphibian passage?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from studies on amphibian road crossings reports that culvert/tunnel use and mortality outcomes are associated with multiple design and contextual factors: wider culverts were used more often (diameter effect), longer culverts were avoided, lighting had mixed effects, natural substrates were used more than artificial substrates, the presence of water had mixed effects, entrance location affected use in one study, and tunnel climate affected use in one study [884]. One study found culverts/tunnels decreased road deaths only when barrier fencing was also installed, and most culverts/tunnels assessed had barrier fencing to guide amphibians to entrances [884]. Certain designs were unsuitable: one-way tunnels with vertical entry chutes resulted in high mortality of common toads, and condensation deposits from steel culverts had very high metal concentrations [884]. Barrier fencing design influenced effectiveness: decreased deaths depended on fence length and material being effective; barriers at least 0.6 m high were required to prevent green frogs and leopard frogs climbing over; some species (treefrogs and 10% of common toads) climbed over fencing during breeding migrations [756]. Reported use rates varied widely (e.g., 15\u201385% of individuals, 3\u201315 species; some studies reported <10% use or no use), and in one case thousands of amphibians were still killed on the road [884].",
